p: Phytochemical T8, egenine, has a binding energy of −9.2 kcal/mol. T8 is an isoquinoline alkaloid produced by Fumaria vaillantii. In traditional medicine, Fumaria vaillantii has been reported to exhibit antifungal, anti-inflammatory and anti-psychotic activities [ 45]. Supplementary Figure S3b shows the TMPRSS2 residues that form hydrogen bonds or π-π stacking interactions with T8. The two 1,3-dioxole groups present in T8 form hydrogen bonds with G383, E388, E389 and A400. One of the hydroxyl groups present in T8 forms C-H⋯O type hydrogen bond with residue C437. Further, T8 forms hydrophobic contacts with residues T387, A399, E388, N398, E260, and A466.
